courses.learning_outcomes:
At the end of the course of studies, students will have acquired the ability to
1. write, compile and execute Python programs;
2. make use of Python's object-oriented programming methodology;
3. make use of Python's functional programming methodology;
4. design and create applications using Python modules;
5. include other programming languages (e.g., C programming language) into Python;
6. use Python for database and web access;
7. use Python for 2D and 3D visualization.

Upon successful completion of the course, the students will have acquired the ability to:

1. appreciate that concepts of signals and systems can be used in a wide variety of disciplines and applications;

2. recognize the power of working in transform domains; to take advantage of the complementary insights and tools that these
different perspectives provide;

3. recognize system properties such as causality, stability, linearity, and time invariance;

4. perform time-domain analysis of linear time-invariant (LTI) systems; in particular performing convolution in continuous and
discrete time;

5. analyze LTI systems and their properties through determination and examination of the impulse response;

6. use and compute Fourier series to analyze periodic signals and the response of LTI systems to such signals;

7. use Fourier transform methods to analyze general signals, including both aperiodic and periodic signals;

8. use frequency domain methods to analyze the effects of LTI filters on signals;

9. understand the sampling theorem and, more generally, the impact in both the time and frequency domains of sampling;

10. analyze signals and LTI systems using Laplace transforms; and

11. analyze signals and LTI systems using z-transforms.

Upon successful completion of the course, the students will have acquired the ability to:

1. demonstrate basic knowledge and understanding of digital communications;

2. follow methods and algorithms commonly used in digital communications;

3. apply principles and analytical techniques to investigate simple digital communication systems;

4. compare different algorithms and analytical techniques in digital communications, and the strengths and weaknesses of
different digital communication systems; and

5. design and optimize simple digital communication systems.

Upon successful completion of the course, the students will have acquired the ability to:

1. understand the process and steps of discrete-event simulation modeling;

2. demonstrate a basic understanding of how any simulation language computes its answers;

3. specify ways a computer can generate uniform and non-uniform random numbers;

4. select statistical models for simulation input;

5. use statistical techniques to determine the statistics of the simulation output;

6. use statistical techniques to determine which of two simulated systems is better; and

7. analyze a real situation, model it, and then build a simulation model to test hypotheses.

Upon successful completion of the course, the students will have acquired the ability to:

1. understand the basic principles in the Markov Chain and Martingale;

2. acquire intuitive concepts underlying the basic theory of stochastic processes;

3. associate some key concepts with short mnemonic expressions so that the acquired knowledge can last a long time;

4. appreciate the role and function of probability models in problem analysis;

5. improve their general ability of logical reasoning and clear presentation; and

6. acquire the capability of using simulations as a principled/reinforced method in evaluating systems/situations with randomness.

Upon completion of this course, students will:
1. gain conceptual knowledge in the social and human dimensions of social media;
2. gain conceptual as well as practical knowledge in social media modeling and analysis;
3. be able to integrate theories and concepts in human information interaction into the analytics and visualization of large scale social media.

Upon completing the class, the students should:
i) Understand the working principles and engineering trade-offs in the design and implementation of various e-payment systems and cryptocurrency technologies ;
ii) Have the ability to analyze and evaluate the applicability and limitations of different e-payment and cryptocurrency-based solutions under different deployment scenarios.

courses.course_syllabus:
The course introduces e-payment systems and cryptocurrency technologies. Topics to be covered include:
- Introduction to Money and Banking;
- Automated Clearing and Settlement Systems;
- B2B payment systems;
- E-payment security/ privacy and the related protocols;
- Smartcard technologies;
- Digital Wallets and Mobile payment systems;
- Peer-to-peer payment services;
- E-cash and Cryptocurrencies;
- Block-chain technologies and their emerging applications;
- The Future of Money and Technology.

courses.learning_outcomes:
Upon successful completion of the course, the students will have acquired the ability to:

1. understand the basic transmission characteristics of optical fiber;

2. understand the basic structure and properties of optical sources and detectors in optical transmission systems;

3. understand the basic structure and properties of common optical components in optical systems and networks;

4. design simple optical transmission systems and evaluate its system performance; and

5. appreciate different kind of optical systems and networks.

Upon successful completion of the course, the students will have acquired the ability to:

1 demonstrate Knowledge and understanding of essential concepts, methods, and technologies of crytography;

2. understand various cryptographic primitives, their security properties, and applicaitons.

Upon successful completion of the course, students will have acquired the ability to:
1. Understand basic image processing techniques, including 2D signal processing, image priors, image filtering, edge detection, and image denoising;
2. Understand techniques for mid-level visual understanding, including estimating motion information from images, stereo matching, depth prediction, 3D geometric estimation from images, image feature matching, and panorama stitching;
3. Understand techniques for high-level visual understanding, including image segmentation and image generation;
4. Design an image processing pipeline to enhance image quality and extract mid-level visual information;
5. Develop Python programming skills to implement image processing and visual understanding algorithms;
6. Develop programming skills to utilize existing computer vision and neural network toolboxes for enhancing images, extracting geometric information, and extracting semantic information from images.

Upon successful completion of the course, the students will have acquired the ability to:
1. describe the relation of global and local coordinate systems and their transformations;
2. discuss the mechanisms of state-of-the-art positioning technologies and their underlying principles, together with their corresponding merits and limitations;
3. use a range of techniques to design positioning systems in indoor and outdoor environments;
4. understand the performance metrics for positioning systems.

Upon successful completion of the course, the students will have acquired the ability to:
1. Understand the cryptographic concepts of blockchain as a distributed ledger;
2. Describe the issues of trust, anonymity and consensus mechanisms;
3. Describe and understand the differences between different types of blockchain structures;
4. Understand the applications of blockchain in various applications, as well as their challenges.

This is a companion lab course for IERG4090. This lab offers more advanced network design, implementation, and troubleshooting experiments for students to gain in-depth hands-on knowledge and practical experiences.

Upon successful completion of the lab, the students will have acquired the ability to:
1. Configure and deploy hub, bridges and switches;
2. Configure and deploy intra-domain and inter-domain routing;
3. Devise network plan according to requirements and constraints.

Upon successful completion of the course, the students will have acquired the ability to:
1. Understand how enterprise networks and cloud operation and interact with each other in the real world Internet environment;
2. Setup and manage a two-layer firewall network architecture and appreciate its effectiveness;
3. Design and implement secure tunnel between main office and data center;
4. Design and implement an enterprise level wireless LAN with both security and user friendly features;
5. Design and implement a basic private cloud infrastructure at private site and data center.
6. Design and implement a basic IPv6 network infrastructure at local site.
7. Design and implement an IPv6 connection to remote client mobile devices.
8. Setup a VPN connection for remote management device ;
9. Perform basic network monitoring and debugging; Unlike traditional lab course, no detail design plan or implementation steps are provided for the students. Students need to figure out the solution by themselves according to the problem specification. We treat students as engineers and want to train up their skills in network design, peer collaboration, problem solving, and protocol debugging under a setting which is similar to the real-world environment.

Students will learn the basic analytical skills for telecommunication networks. Even though the course focuses on the switching networks, the methodologies can be generalized and applied to the design and analysis of routing algorithms and protocols of wired and wireless networks. Upon successful completion of the course, the students will have acquired the ability to:

1. appreciate the role and function of switching system in communication networks;

2. understand the basic principles in switching system and learn the important issues concerning the switching system
design;

3. understand the topological design and routing properties of some well-known switching network, such as the Clos
Network, Benes network and Banyan network, etc. Specifically, the students should be familiar with the connections
between graph theory and routing algorithms of network; and

4. understand the design of switches with multicasting capability;

5. apply probability theory to analyze the performance of components in telecommunications networks.

6. a general appreciation of how mathematical analysis can be applied to engineering systems to quantify their performance.
